## Goals {#goals}

Alien Arena’s premise is that players are under time crunch to secure their safety for one more round, hoping that eventually they can escape the loop. The “carrots” that drive player actions on the map include engaging character design, build crafting, and exploration. The “stick” is the fear of losing the game due to scarce resources in a harsh environment. **Objectives should feel like the primary means of surviving from round to round**.

* We want objectives to engage players’ tactical decision making and problem solving without being punishingly hard.  
* Players should be able to leverage their build’s strengths to selectively complete certain objectives faster.  
* Players should have to team up to complete complex objectives in a way that is satisfying and collaborative.  
* Objectives should be touchpoints that implicitly guide players through map exploration.

## Definitions {#definitions}

An **Objective** is a mini-game that appears on the map in Alien Arena. All Objectives have a visual indicator to grab the player’s attention. Below is a very simple example that we’ll call “Alien Scrapyard.” Here the player encounters a small tile set with loads of metal bits. The player can interact with the pile to acquire metal but they are **slowed** due to the weight. Depositing the metal back at the ship removes **slowed** and completes the objective.

* **Interactive** \- All Objectives need to be started manually.   
  * No Objectives begin without player intervention.  
* **Time** \- Initiating any Objective costs the player time. There are no “instant pickup” objectives.   
  * However, certain builds can significantly shorten the time required to complete an objective.  
* **Challenge** \- On top of being a time sink, Objectives should provide a hurdle to overcome. *These should be highly varied*.  
* **Target** \- All Objectives have a clear end state that is visible after a player has initiated it.  
* **Persistence** \- Once an Objective has been completed, it is visually distinct from its previous state.  
* **Reward** \- All Objectives produce a positive outcome(s). *These should be highly varied*.

   1. Use salvage to repair the turret. Defend it from a few enemies (does not require kill potential) while it calibrates targeting. Terminates with a functioning auto-turret.  
5. Forgotten Lockbox  
   1. Encounter a chest\! Interact to open the puzzle interface. Solve the puzzle to open the chest and terminate the objective.  
      1. Puzzle is simple and visual. (maze, \#squares, 2D rubik’s, etc)  
      2. Attacking the chest has a 50% chance to destroy the item inside  
6. Power Cable  
   1. There’s an item on a pedestal but it looks inert. Follow the nearby power cable to the break and reconnect it. Terminates with an item accessible on the pedestal.  
7. Restore Greenhouse  
   1. Follow a pipe from the greenhouse and use scrap to repair the break. Turn on the water at the greenhouse to terminate the Objective.  
8. Save the Frogs  
   1. Three interactable frogs are a short distance from a nearby pond. Terminates when all frogs are in the pond.  
9. Recover Probe  
   1. A short-range probe from the ship became embedded in the ground. Dig it out and interact to give it coordinates back to the ship. Terminates at the ship where the probe presents a reward.  
10. Noxious Gas  
    1. A damaging gas cloud dissuades entry to part of the map. Muddle through the gas and kick in the spores producing it. Terminates by dispersing the gas and loot pops out of the spores.  
11. Salvage Medpacks  
    1. Hostile wildlife is attracted to the smell of a pod full of medical supplies. Fight them off to recover the supplies. Terminates when the pod has been interacted with. Healing pickups appear.  
12. Capture Outpost  
    1. Hostile forces have set up camp. Terminates when all encamped enemies are dead. Ends patrols in a short range.  
13. Little John  
    1. A gate is guarded by a single, large enemy. It only attacks when someone approaches the gate. Terminates when the gate has been interacted with. If the enemy is still alive, it gains \+5 Berserk.

## Rewards Structure {#rewards-structure}

As a rule, completing objectives and participating in combat should always reward the player *somehow*. We want some rewards to be deterministic (i.e. a given objective gives an expected reward) but others to be pseudo-random so they can be exciting\! (i.e. a rare item drop)
